🧩 Fixing “SSL Certificate Not Trusted” in Chrome
🧠 Background
Chrome uses its own certificate store (NSS DB) that doesn’t automatically trust system certificates.
Even though your VM already trusts the Calix Root and Intermediate CAs, Chrome requires these certificates to be imported manually into your user-level NSS DB.
🧰 Steps
Step 1 – Verify certificates exist
Make sure your system already has the Calix certificates installed:

ls /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/
You should see:
CalixROOTCA.crt
CalixInterCA.crt
CalixEntCA.crt

{note:title=If any are missing|icon=false}
Contact EngOps before proceeding.
{note}

Step 2 – Create NSS DB

mkdir -p ~/.pki/nssdb
certutil -N -d sql:~/.pki/nssdb --empty-password
{warning:title=If you are asked for a password|icon=false}
That means an old NSS DB already exists.
Run the cleanup commands below, then retry the above:
rm -rf ~/.pki/nssdb
mkdir -p ~/.pki/nssdb
certutil -N -d sql:~/.pki/nssdb --empty-password
{warning}

Step 3 – Import Calix Certificates
certutil -d sql:~/.pki/nssdb -A -t "C,," -n "CalixRootCA" -i /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/CalixROOTCA.crt
certutil -d sql:~/.pki/nssdb -A -t "C,," -n "CalixInterCA" -i /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/CalixInterCA.crt
certutil -d sql:~/.pki/nssdb -A -t "C,," -n "CalixEntCA" -i /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/CalixEntCA.crt
(Optional – verify):
certutil -d sql:~/.pki/nssdb -L
Step 4 – Restart Chrome
After importing, close and reopen Chrome.
Try accessing the following internal services:
https://pln-stash.calix.local  
https://tabnine.calix.local  
https://jenkins.calix.local
You should now be able to connect without SSL certificate warnings.
📝 Notes
This fix applies only to Chrome.
It affects browser-level trust — system tools like curl, git, and apt already trust the Calix certificates.
The SSL warning doesn’t block functionality, but this ensures a cleaner user experience.
